				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Each address bit chooses which half of the chip to look at. Consider if you only had 16 data pieces in a chip.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">On chip 1&nbsp; &nbsp; On chip 2&nbsp; &nbsp; <br />Game 1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Game 2<br />data,address|data,address<br />1&nbsp; &nbsp; 0001&nbsp; &nbsp;|1&nbsp; &nbsp; 0001<br />2&nbsp; &nbsp; 0010&nbsp; &nbsp;|2&nbsp; &nbsp; 0010<br />3&nbsp; &nbsp; 0011&nbsp; &nbsp;|3&nbsp; &nbsp; 0011<br />4&nbsp; &nbsp; 0100&nbsp; &nbsp;|4&nbsp; &nbsp; 0100<br />5&nbsp; &nbsp; 0101&nbsp; &nbsp;|5&nbsp; &nbsp; 0101<br />6&nbsp; &nbsp; 0110&nbsp; &nbsp;|6&nbsp; &nbsp; 0110<br />7&nbsp; &nbsp; 0111&nbsp; &nbsp;|7&nbsp; &nbsp; 0111<br />8&nbsp; &nbsp; 1000&nbsp; &nbsp;|8&nbsp; &nbsp; 1000<br />9&nbsp; &nbsp; 1001&nbsp; &nbsp;|9&nbsp; &nbsp; 1001<br />a&nbsp; &nbsp; 1010&nbsp; &nbsp;|a&nbsp; &nbsp; 1010<br />b&nbsp; &nbsp; 1011&nbsp; &nbsp;|b&nbsp; &nbsp; 1011<br />c&nbsp; &nbsp; 1100&nbsp; &nbsp;|c&nbsp; &nbsp; 1100<br />d&nbsp; &nbsp; 1101&nbsp; &nbsp;|d&nbsp; &nbsp; 1101<br />e&nbsp; &nbsp; 1110&nbsp; &nbsp;|e&nbsp; &nbsp; 1110<br />f&nbsp; &nbsp; 1111&nbsp; &nbsp;|f&nbsp; &nbsp; 1111<br />Both on one&nbsp; &nbsp; Game 1&nbsp; &nbsp; <br />data.address&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />1&nbsp; &nbsp; 00001&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />2&nbsp; &nbsp; 00010&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />3&nbsp; &nbsp; 00011&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />4&nbsp; &nbsp; 00100&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />5&nbsp; &nbsp; 00101&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />6&nbsp; &nbsp; 00110&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />7&nbsp; &nbsp; 00111&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />8&nbsp; &nbsp; 01000&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />9&nbsp; &nbsp; 01001&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />a&nbsp; &nbsp; 01010&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />b&nbsp; &nbsp; 01011&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />c&nbsp; &nbsp; 01100&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />d&nbsp; &nbsp; 01101&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />e&nbsp; &nbsp; 01110&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />f&nbsp; &nbsp; 01111&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />Game 2<br />data,address&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />1&nbsp; &nbsp; 10001&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />2&nbsp; &nbsp; 10010&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />3&nbsp; &nbsp; 10011&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />4&nbsp; &nbsp; 10100&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />5&nbsp; &nbsp; 10101&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />6&nbsp; &nbsp; 10110&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />7&nbsp; &nbsp; 10111&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />8&nbsp; &nbsp; 11000&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />9&nbsp; &nbsp; 11001&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />a&nbsp; &nbsp; 11010&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />b&nbsp; &nbsp; 11011&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />c&nbsp; &nbsp; 11100&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />d&nbsp; &nbsp; 11101&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />e&nbsp; &nbsp; 11110&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br />f&nbsp; &nbsp; 11111&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /></div><br />Note that the new fifth address line is 0 for all of game 1, and 1 for all of game 2.<br /><br />If that didn't help, think of it like books. Suppose you have two books, 100 pages long. If you put them in separate books, each book runs pages 0-99. If you put them in one volume, then book 2 will be at pages 100-199. The hundreds digit tells you whether you are in book 1 (0) or book 2 (1).<br /><br />In this way, attaching the switch to the new address line makes it pick whether to use the data from game 1, or the data from game 2.</div>

