					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Ziggy587 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Ahhhh, I think I understand it now. If I use that diagram, do I have to use a diode and cap on the reset line? <br /></div>No, that's only for the NES.<br /><br />(The SNES has a /RESET pin; a front-loading NES with a functioning CIC has a +RESET pin; the Famicom and top-loading NES have nothing at all. In order to work with all NES-like-devices, you have to indirectly figure out whether the NES CPU is being reset, which you can do by checking whether either of M2 or A0 is alternating. That's what the diode &amp; capacitor are doing.)</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

